subSubSection.paragraph:
Description: Female (one of CASENT 9020441 measured): Large sized coelotine, total length 12.50 (
Fig. 63
). Eyes subequal in size, with lateral eyes slightly larger than median eyes (AME 0.19 , ALE 0.24 , PME 0.19 , PLE 0.21 ); anterior eyes equally separated by slightly more than half of their diameter; PME separated from each other by slightly less than their diameter, from PLE by more than PME diameter (AME-AME 0.11 , AME-ALE 0.11 , PME-PME 0.16 , PME-PLE 0.28 , AME-PME 0.22 ) (
Fig. 64
). Chelicerae with 3 promarginal and 4 retromarginal teeth. Labium longer than wide (L/W= 1.20 ) (
Fig. 65
). Epigynal teeth short, arise anteriorly lateral to atrium, separated by more than atrial width; atrium small, with distinct, continuous anterior margin but indistinct lateral margins; copulatory ducts broad, extending anteriorly approximately the length of spermathecae, more or less folded longitudially; spermathecae with small bases and broad stalks; spermathecal heads arise distally from lateral side of spermathecae (
Figs 49 –54
, 58–59 , 69–70 ,
74– 87
).

Male (one of CASENT 9020441 measured): Large sized coelotine, total length 12.00 (
Fig. 66
). Eyes subequal in size, with lateral eyes slightly larger than median eyes (AME 0.19 , ALE 0.22 , PME 0.21 , PLE 0.22 ); AME separated from each other by 2 / 3 of their diameter, from ALE by about ½ of AME diameter; PME separated from each other by slightly less than their diameter, widely separated from PLE by more than PME diameter (AME-AME 0.13 , AME-ALE 0.08 , PME-PME 0.18 , PME-PLE 0.27 , AME-PME 0.24 ) (
Fig. 67
). Chelicera with 3 promarginal and 4 retromarginal teeth. Labium longer than wide (L/W= 1.21 ) (
Fig. 68
). Palpal patellar apophysis large, slightly extending and pointing distally; RTA more than half of tibial length, with distinctly protruding distal end; lateral tibial apophysis broad; cymbial furrow short, less than 1 / 3 of cymbial length; conductor slender, with a dorsal apophysis, a small basal lamella; median apophysis broad, round, spoon-shaped; embolus short, filiform, prolateral in origin (
Figs 55 –57
, 60–62 ,
71– 73
).
